<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.N. APPROVES MILITARY ACTION AGAINST IRAQ 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to "Deadline Could Speed Up the Timetable" (editorial, Nov. 27): 
</P>
<P>
The hope that the United Nation's resolution, allowing the use of force against 
Iraq, will force Hussein to back down could be futile. Hussein is already boxed 
into a no-win situation. 
</P>
<P>
His only "honorable" way out now is for his enemies to attack, then go down in 
defeat on the field of battle. 
</P>
<P>
We still have another option, time. To allow time for the embargo to rot the 
will and ability of the Iraqi military and people to sustain their position. 
This is really a test of wills between the so-called free world and the 
barbarian, Hussein. Hussein understands this. The question is, do we? 
</P>
<P>
I think many in the military know that pulling "hard time" in the desert is 
better than an "early out" in a body bag. It's too bad that those making our 
decisions aren't faced with the same option. 
</P>
<P>
DON LOVE, Palm Springs 
</P>
</TEXT>
