<P>
BANGLADESH LEADER TO QUIT SOON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DHAKA, Bangladesh 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Hussain Mohammed Ershad bowed to an increasingly violent campaign for 
his ouster and agreed today to quit as soon as the opposition nominates a 
replacement, state radio said. 
</P>
<P>
Parliament will meet Saturday to try to choose a successor, the radio said in a 
late-night news bulletin. 
</P>
<P>
Ershad had offered Monday to step down shortly before elections scheduled for 
June, but the opposition, which had staged a seven-week campaign to drive him 
from office, rebuffed that offer and demanded he step down now. 
</P>
<P>
The 60-year-old former army general took over Bangladesh, one of the world's 
poorest countries, in a bloodless coup in 1982. He had declared a state of 
emergency Nov. 27 to quash the opposition campaign seeking his ouster. 
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the announcement, hundreds of opposition workers thronged the 
streets of the capital, chanting slogans and setting off firecrackers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
